'''Middlesbrough Football Club''' {{IPAc-en|<U+02C8>|m|<U+026A>|d|<U+0259>l|z|b|r|<U+0259>}}, also known as  '''''Boro''''', are an English [[association football|football]] club based in [[Middlesbrough]], who play in the [[Football League Championship]]. Formed in 1876, they have played at the [[Riverside Stadium]] since August 1995,<ref name="RSStadium">{{cite web|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-club-info/|title=Boro FC club info|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070904115147/http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-club-info/|archivedate=4 September 2007|publisher=gazettelive.co.uk|accessdate=27 May 2008}}</ref> their third ground since turning professional in 1889. Their longest-serving home was [[Ayresome Park]], where they played for 92 years, from 1903 to 1995.

They were one of the founding members of the Premier League in 1992. The club's main rivals are [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]],<ref name="fan survey"/> however the club also takes part in [[Yorkshire]] derbies with several other Yorkshire clubs; most notably [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref name="fan survey"/>

The club's highest league finish to date was third in the [[1913<U+2013>14 in English football|1913<U+2013>14]] season and they have only spent two seasons outside of [[the Football League]]'s top two divisions.<ref name="MFCHistBk1"/> The club came close to folding in 1986 after experiencing severe financial difficulties before the club was saved by a [[consortium]] led by then board member and later chairman [[Steve Gibson (businessman)|Steve Gibson]].<ref name="PremierLeagueSite"/> Middlesbrough were controversially deducted three points for failing to fulfil a fixture against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] during the [[1996<U+2013>97 FA Premier League|1996<U+2013>97 Premier League season]] and were subsequently relegated.<ref name="PremierLeague96/97">{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/content/premierleague/en-gb/matchday/results.html?paramSeason=1996-1997&view=.dateSeason |title=Season 1996/97|accessdate=27 May 2008 |publisher=[[Premier League]]}}</ref> They were promoted the following season and spent eleven consecutive seasons in the top division before relegation.<ref name="PremierLeagueSite">{{cite web|url=http://origin-www.premierleague.com/page/middlesbrough |title=Middlesbrough, Official Site of the Premier League|accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=[[Premier League]]}}</ref> Middlesbrough won the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] in 2004, the club's first and only major trophy.<ref name="LgCpFinal"/> They reached the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]] in May 2006 but were beaten by Spanish side [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]]. On 24 May 2009, Middlesbrough were relegated to [[Football League Championship|the Championship]], failing to extend their 11-year stay in the [[Premier League]].<ref name="relegation-from-prem">{{Cite news
  | last = Parrish
  | first = Rob
  | title = Premier League round-up
  | work=Sky Sports
  | publisher=BSkyB
  | date = 24 May 2009
  | url = http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11680_5346133,00.html
  | accessdate =22 May 2010}}</ref>

The club's traditional kit is red with white detailing. The various crests throughout the club's history, the most recent of which was adopted in May 2007,<ref name="newcrest">{{cite news | date=12 May 2007 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/1392479.boro_change_badge_to_reflect_history/ | title=Boro change badge to reflect history |work=The Northern Echo | accessdate=10 October 2008|author=Matt Westcott}}</ref> incorporate a lion rampant.

==History==
{{For|a season-by-season record of league and cup performances|Middlesbrough F.C. seasons}}
{{Main|History of Middlesbrough F.C.}}

[[File:Middlesbrough FC Finishing Positions.jpg|thumb|right|Middlesbrough's finishing positions since entry to the [[Football League]]]]
They won the [[FA Amateur Cup]] in 1895 and again in 1898. The club turned professional in 1889, but reverted to amateur status in 1892.<ref name="MFCHistBk1">{{cite book|last=Glasper|first=Harry|title=Middlesbrough A Complete Record 1876<U+2013>1989|publisher=Breedon Books Sport|isbn=0-907969-53-4}}</ref> They turned professional permanently in 1899.<ref name="Hist76-02">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/club-history/0,,1~51936,00.html |title=Club History <U+2013> Birth of The Boro: 1876<U+2013>1902 |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. }}</ref> After three seasons, they won promotion to the [[Football League First Division|First Division]], where they would remain for the next {{nowrap|22 years}}.<ref name="MFCHistBk1"/>

In 1903, the club moved to [[Ayresome Park]], their home for the next {{nowrap|92 years}}. In 1905, the club sanctioned the transfer of [[Alf Common]] for [[Pound sterling|<U+00A3>]]1,000, a record fee.<ref name="AlfCommon">{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/battling-boro-125-years-3842065 |title=Battling with the Boro for 125 years |work=Evening Gazette |date=21 October 2003 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> Over the next few years, their form fluctuated greatly, rising to sixth in [[1907<U+2013>08 in English football|1907<U+2013>08]] before dropping to seventeenth two seasons later. The club rose to their highest league finish to date, third, in [[1913<U+2013>14 in English football|1913<U+2013>14]].<ref name="Hist03-WW2">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/club-history/0,,1~352488,00.html |title=Club History <U+2013> Early Years: 1903-World War II |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. }}</ref> The First World War soon intervened and football was suspended.
In 2012 Boro went on to win the league
Before league football resumed, Middlesbrough won the Northern Victory League, but the team were unable to maintain their previous form and finished the [[1919<U+2013>20 in English football|1919<U+2013>20]] season in mid-table. They remained in the First Division for the next few seasons, but were relegated in [[1923<U+2013>24 in English football|1923<U+2013>24]] after finishing bottom, ten points adrift of their nearest rivals.<ref name="LeagueResults">
{{cite web|url=http://www.middlesbrough-mad.co.uk/league_history/middlesbrough/index.shtml |title=League history |publisher=Middlesbrough Mad |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> Three seasons later, they won the [[Football League Division Two|Division Two]] title. During that season, debutant [[George Camsell]], who had signed from [[Third Division North]] side Durham City the previous season, finished with a record 59 league goals, which included nine hat tricks. He would continue as top scorer for each of the next ten seasons.<ref name="Camsell">{{cite web|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-legends/2007/07/27/george-camsell-84229-19531247/ |title=George Camsell |publisher=gazettelive.co.uk |accessdate=26 May 2008 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071103124051/http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-legends/2007/07/27/george-camsell-84229-19531247/ |archivedate = 3 November 2007}}</ref> Their tenure back in the top flight lasted only one season, and the club were relegated. They were promoted at the first attempt in [[1928<U+2013>29 in English football|1928<U+2013>29]], winning another Second Division title. The club remained in the First Division until 1954.

The decade before the war saw the emergence of [[Wilf Mannion]] and [[George Hardwick]], both of whom would go on to become [[England national football team|England]] internationals in the years ahead. Middlesbrough climbed to fourth in the last full season before [[World War II|the Second World War]] and were expected to challenge for the title next season, but the war intervened.<ref name="MFCHistBk1"/> After the war, the club was unable to recover the form of the previous seasons and hovered around mid-table and exited in the early rounds of the [[FA Cup]]. Soon afterwards the team began to falter, eventually suffering relegation in [[1953<U+2013>54 in English football|1953<U+2013>54]]. This was the start of a 20-year spell outside the top division, but saw the emergence of one of the club's top goalscorers, [[Brian Clough]], who scored 204 goals in 222 games, before he left for [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]].<ref name="Clough">{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/2004/sep/21/guardianobituaries.football |title=Obituary: Brian Clough |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate=26 May 2008  | first=Brian | last=Glanville | date=20 September 2004}}</ref> Over that period, Middlesbrough maintained reasonable progress in the Second Division but were never serious contenders for promotion. After a fourth place finish in [[1962<U+2013>63 in English football|1962<U+2013>63]], the club endured a steady decline and were relegated to the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] for the first time in their history in 1966.

New manager [[Stan Anderson]] returned the club to the second flight at the first attempt. Middlesbrough would not finish below ninth during the next eight seasons.<ref name="LeagueResults"/> By 1974, [[Jack Charlton]] had taken over as manager and guided the team back to the top flight. They ensured promotion as early as 23 March, and with eight games of the season left, they became runaway champions, finishing with a record 65 points.<ref name="Hist45-86">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/club-history/0,,1~352495,00.html |title=Club History <U+2013> Mannion, Hardwick, Clough and Charlton: 1945 to 1986 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> Middlesbrough won their first silverware as a professional side in [[1975<U+2013>76 in English football|the 1975<U+2013>76 season]], lifting the [[Anglo-Scottish Cup]] in its inaugural season after a two-legged final win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref name="Anglo-Scottish">{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/anglo-scottish-cup/1975-1976/results/fn |title=Anglo-Scottish Cup 1975-1976 : Final |publisher=Statto |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref><ref name="Hist45-86" />

The club experienced severe financial difficulties during the mid-1980s. Middlesbrough were dropping down the table, and finished nineteenth in the [[1984<U+2013>85 in English football|1984<U+2013>85 season]]. In April 1986 the club had to borrow <U+00A3>30,000 from the [[Professional Footballers' Association|PFA]] to pay wages. The final game of the season saw Middlesbrough relegated to the Third Division once more.<ref name="MFCHistBk1"/> That summer, the club called in the [[Official Receiver|Provisional Liquidator]] and shortly afterwards, the club was wound up and the gates to Ayresome Park were padlocked. Without the <U+00A3>350,000 capital required for [[Football League]] registration, a new rule, it seemed inevitable that the club would fold permanently.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/just-37-days-save-club-3773580 |title=Just 37 days to save our club |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=gazettelive.co.uk}}</ref> However, [[Steve Gibson (businessman)|Steve Gibson]], a member of the board at the time, brought together a consortium and with ten minutes to spare before the deadline, they completed their registration with the Football League for the [[1986<U+2013>87 in English football|1986<U+2013>87 season]].<ref name="liquidation">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/4976108.stm |title=Uefa final caps Boro fairytale |accessdate=25 May 2008 |publisher=BBC | date=14 February 2014}}</ref> Following the registration came both a change of club crest and a change of the official company name to Middlesbrough Football and Athletic Club (1986) Ltd.<ref name="Hist86-Pres">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/club-history/0,,1~352502,00.html |title=Club History <U+2013> Winners at Last! 1986 to present |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.}}</ref>

Over the next two seasons, Middlesbrough gained successive promotions into Division Two and then into Division One. The next season though, they came straight back down to Division Two, and with it came the then British transfer record move of [[Gary Pallister]] to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] for <U+00A3>2.3&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A18740513 |title=Manchester United: The Sir Alex Era <U+2013> Part 1 |accessdate=28 May 2007 |publisher=BBC }}</ref> Despite constant promotion and relegation, Middlesbrough were founding members of the [[FA Premier League]] for the [[FA Premier League 1992<U+2013>93|1992<U+2013>93]] season.<ref name="PremierLeagueSite" />

Player-manager [[Bryan Robson]], from [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], took charge in 1994 and Middlesbrough were brought back into national attention.<ref name="Bryan Robson">{{cite web|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/middlesbrough-fc-anthony-vickers-countdown-4043321 |title=Anthony Vickers' countdown of Boro's top 40 signings |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=Gazette Live }}</ref> Following promotion to the Premier League and high-profile purchases like diminutive Brazilian [[Juninho Paulista|Juninho]], many considered Middlesbrough were on the way up.<ref name="PremierLeagueSite" /> However, a difficult [[FA Premier League 1996<U+2013>97|1996<U+2013>97]] season was compounded by a deduction of three points imposed just after Christmas, as punishment for the club's failure to fulfil a fixture against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn]], which ultimately resulted in relegation.<ref name="PremierLeague96/97"/> Without the points deduction, the club would have had enough points to avoid relegation. At the same time, the club managed to reach both the League and [[FA Cup|FA]] Cup finals for the first time, but lost out in both. Despite being in the second tier they were again runners up in the League Cup final the next year.<ref name="Hist86-Pres"/>

Despite losing high profile players [[Fabrizio Ravanelli]] and [[Juninho Paulista|Juninho]] due to relegation, Middlesbrough were promoted back to the Premiership at the first attempt in 1998. The following season saw them settle well and they enjoyed a 12-game unbeaten run midway through [[FA Premier League 1998<U+2013>99|1998<U+2013>99]], including a 3<U+2013>2 win at [[Old Trafford]] in January during which they took a 3<U+2013>0 lead. It was United's only home defeat during their treble winning season. They continued to stay secure in mid-table the following season, thanks mainly to the goals of [[Hamilton Ricard]] and the signings of big name players such as [[Paul Ince]] and [[Christian Ziege]]. In [[FA Premier League 2000<U+2013>01|2000<U+2013>01]] they had a brief relegation scare that was solved with the arrival of [[Terry Venables]] as co-manager, and a 3<U+2013>0 win away at [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in March was the team's best result. The trend of buying European stars continued with the acquisitions of [[Christian Karembeu]] and [[Alen Bok<U+0161>i<U+0107>]].

Bryan Robson left the club before the start of [[FA Premier League 2001<U+2013>02|2001<U+2013>02]] season, having served as manager for 7 years, and was replaced by Manchester United assistant coach [[Steve McClaren]]. The following seasons saw Premiership security maintained as Middlesbrough slowly improved and were seen as a tough side to beat when playing at the Riverside Stadium. During McClaren's reign, Middlesbrough achieved their highest Premier league placing of 7th in the [[2004-05 Premier League|2004-05 season]].

[[File:MillenniumStadiumInside.jpg|The [[Football League Cup Final 2004|2004 League Cup Final]] at the [[Millennium Stadium]].|right|thumb]]
The [[2003<U+2013>04 Middlesbrough F.C. season|2003<U+2013>04]] season was the most successful in the club's history as they finally won a major trophy after beating [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton]] 2<U+2013>1 in the League Cup final under manager [[Steve McClaren]].<ref name="LgCpFinal">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3507795.stm |title=Boro lift Carling Cup |accessdate=21 May 2007 |date=29 February 2004 |publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref> This success also ensured that Middlesbrough would qualify for Europe <U+2013> the [[UEFA Cup]] <U+2013> for the first time, in which they reached the last 16. UEFA cup qualification was achieved for the second consecutive year after a dramatic 1<U+2013>1 away draw with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] thanks to a late penalty save from [[Mark Schwarzer]] in the last game of the season.<ref name="Results0405">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2359695/City-pay-the-penalty-for-Fowler-miss.html|title=City pay the penalty for Fowler miss|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |accessdate=14 February 2014  | first=Tim | last=Rich | date=16 May 2005}}</ref>

Middlesbrough reached the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]] in [[Eindhoven]], following two comebacks from 3<U+2013>0 down in the rounds preceding it,<ref name="UEFACpQt">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/4875620.stm |title=Middlesbrough 4<U+2013>1 Basle |accessdate=28 May 2007 |date=6 April 2004 |publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref><ref name="UEFACpSm">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/4933504.stm|title=M'brough 4<U+2013>2 S B'chrst |accessdate=28 May 2007 |date=27 April 2004 |publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref> but lost 4<U+2013>0 to [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]].<ref name="Results0506">{{cite web| url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=420487.html |title=Sevilla run away with trophy |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=UEFA}}</ref> Following the cup final, McClaren left to head up the [[England national football team|England team]], and captain [[Gareth Southgate]] took over, despite not having the coaching qualifications, but he was allowed to continue after receiving special dispensation.<ref name="GateCoachingBadges">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2350882/Southgate-wins-coaching-badge-appeal.html|title=Southgate wins coaching badges appeal|date=23 November 2006|accessdate=14 February 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK  | first=Rob | last=Stewart}}</ref> During the [[2007<U+2013>08 Middlesbrough F.C. season|2007<U+2013>08]] season, Southgate broke Middlesbrough's record transfer fee, paying <U+00A3>13.6&nbsp;million for [[Brazil national football team|Brazilian]] striker [[Afonso Alves]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2291155/Afonso-Alves-eyes-Middlesbrough-debut.html |title=Afonso Alves eyes Middlesbrough debut |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK |date=6 February 2008|accessdate=14 February 2014  | first=Richard | last=Bright}}</ref> Southgate's first two seasons saw the club finish in 12th and 13th places. He oversaw the club reaching the quarter finals of the FA Cup for three seasons, but the club was relegated to the [[Football League Championship]] on the last day of the [[Middlesbrough F.C. season 2008<U+2013>09|2008<U+2013>09 season]]. Southgate was sacked in October 2009, and replaced by [[Gordon Strachan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2009/oct/26/gordon-strachan-middlesbrough-new-manager|title=
Gordon Strachan confirmed as Middlesbrough's new manager|work=the guardian |location=UK |accessdate=26 October 2009  | date=26 October 2009}}</ref> At the time of Southgate's dismissal, Boro were fourth in the Championship and only one point away from the automatic promotion spot,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/middlesbrough/2009-2010/table/2009-10-21|title=Middlesbrough 2009-2010 : English League Championship Table on 21 October 2009|accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> but their form under Strachan was significantly worse and they finished mid-table.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/middlesbrough/2009-2010/table|title=Middlesbrough 2009-2010 : English League Championship Table at end of season|accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>

Despite starting the 2010<U+2013>11 campaign as promotion favourites, the club endured a disappointing start to the season securing only 1-point in 5 away games. Having slipped to 20th in the Championship following a home defeat to rivals Leeds, Strachan resigned on 18 October. A week later, [[Tony Mowbray]] was confirmed as the new manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/9128153.stm |title=Middlesbrough name Tony Mowbray as new manager |accessdate=18 March 2012 |date=26 October 2010 |publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref>  Having staved off the threat of relegation, Mowbray successfully transformed Boro's fortunes, eventually guiding them to a top-half finish. Boro ended the season top of the form table after four consecutive league wins, the first such run since 1998. However, despite a magnificent first half of the season, Boro failed to capitalise, and finished 7th in the League, missing out on the play-offs by 5 points and 1 position.

Following a poor run of form of 2 wins in 12 games in the 2013<U+2013>14 campaign, on 21 October 2013, nearly 3 years after his arrival, [[Tony Mowbray]] left the club with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~3505015,00.html |title=Middlesbrough &#124; Tony Mowbray Leaves Boro |publisher=Mfc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=8 December 2013}}</ref> [[Aitor Karanka]], a former Spanish defender and assistant coach at [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] became the new Middlesbrough manager on 13 November 2013, signing a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24925713 |title= Aitor Karanka: Middlesbrough name ex-Real Madrid man as boss |work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC |date=13 November 2013 |accessdate=8 December 2013}}</ref> He became the first non-British manager at the club.

