}}

[[File:Middlesbrough crest old.png|right|thumb|Middlesbrough F.C. crest 1986<U+2013>2007|200px]]
Middlesbrough's original home kit upon election to the Football League in 1899 was a white home shirt with blue shorts and they did not adopt their colours of red and white until later that season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Middlesbrough/Middlesbrough.htm|title=Middlesbrough|publisher=Historical Football Kits|accessdate=21 May 2008}}</ref> Previous kits included a white shirt with a blue and white [[polka dot]]ted collar from around 1889. The Middlesbrough kit has remained broadly the same over the years with a red shirt and socks and either red or white shorts. The distinctive broad white stripe across the chest was introduced by Jack Charlton in 1973 (following an attempt to change the home shirt to a [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United-style]] white shirt) and brought back for a one-off in 1997<U+2013>98 and then again for the 2000<U+2013>01 and 2004<U+2013>05 seasons due to popular demand.<ref name="chestband">{{cite news|date=30 December 2007|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~1201014,00.html|title=Take Part in Boro's Battle of the Band|publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.|accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> The club subsequently announced in December 2007 that the club would allow the fans to decide via an online and text vote whether the white band should return for the [[Middlesbrough F.C. season 2008<U+2013>09|following season]].<ref name="chestband" /> On 8 January 2008 the club announced that the white band was to return, with 77.4% of voters voting in its favour, with the fans to choose the final shirt design from a selection of three designs,<ref name="whiteband">{{cite news|date=8 January 2008|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~1209302,00.html|title=We're Backing The Band|publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.|accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> of which the winner was announced on 7 May 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~1307364,00.html |title=The Band Is Back! |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |date=7 May 2008 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>

The Middlesbrough crest has gone through four changes since the formation of the club. Initially, the badge was simply the town of Middlesbrough's crest with a red lion instead of a blue lion in order to fit in with the club's colours. Following the adoption of the white band on the shirts in 1973, only the red lion remained with the letters "M.F.C" underneath in red. This was further adapted following the reformation of the club in 1986 to a circular crest with the lion in the middle and the words "Middlesbrough Football Club 1986" around the circle in order to reflect this new era. In 2007, Middlesbrough changed their crest once again, this time with the lion inside a shield and the words "Middlesbrough Football Club 1876" underneath.<ref name="newcrest"/> The club stated that this was to reflect the club's long history and not just their post-liquidation status.<ref name="newcrest"/>

Since the [[Middlesbrough F.C. season 2009<U+2013>10|2009<U+2013>10 season]], Middlesbrough's kit has been produced by [[adidas]], replacing the previous deal with [[Errea]] which had lasted for 15 years.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/errea-dropped-favour-global-brand-3719674| title= Errea dropped in favour of global brand adidas | work=Evening Gazette | date=31 March 2009 | accessdate=14 February 2014 }}</ref> The kit is only available in the UK from the official club shops and Middlesbrough's online store.<ref>{{cite news | date=23 December 2005 | url=http://www.comeonboro.com/interviews/140006.htm | title=DAVE ALLAN INTERVIEW 23<U+2013>12<U+2013>05 | publisher=ComeOnBoro.com | accessdate=22 May 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070407170032/http://www.comeonboro.com/interviews/140006.htm |archivedate = 7 April 2007}}</ref> The club's shirt sponsor was announced on 20 July 2007 as [[satellite navigation|satellite navigation device]] manufacturers [[Garmin]].<ref>{{cite news | date=28 June 2007 | url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~1063181,00.html | title=Boro Sponsorship Talks Ongoing |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. | accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date = 20 July 2007|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~1076097,00.html |title=Boro Announce New Sponsor|publisher="mfc.co.uk"|accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> This contract was extended until the end of the [[Middlesbrough F.C. season 2008<U+2013>09|2008<U+2013>09 season]] in a deal described as "the biggest in the club's history".<ref>{{cite news | date=18 January 2008 | url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/boros-biggest-shirt-signing-history-3736492| title=Boro's Biggest Shirt Signing in History| publisher=eveninggazettelive.co.uk | accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>
As of the start of the 2011/2012 season Middlesbrough will be sponsored by Ramsdens pawnbrokers.

