==Stadium==
[[File:Riverside Stadium front.jpg|right|thumb|The Riverside Stadium in 2006, with the old gates to Ayresome Park in the foreground]]
{{Main|Ayresome Park|Riverside Stadium}}

After formation in 1876, and with the club still amateurs, Middlesbrough's first two years of football were played at [[Albert Park, Middlesbrough|Albert Park]] in Middlesbrough. After seeing the damage being caused by players and supporters, the Park Committee ordered the club to find an alternate venue. The club moved to Breckon Hill, behind the present-day [[Middlesbrough College]], after agreeing to rent the land from its owner. However, two years later in 1880, the owner increased the rent and the club decided to move. They moved into the [[Linthorpe Road West (Cricket Ground)|Linthorpe Road Ground]] in 1882, home at the time of Middlesbrough Cricket Club. The cricket club departed in 1893<U+2013>94 to move to the Breckon Hill field, and Middlesbrough Football Club became sole users of the ground.<ref name="GroundsHistory"/>

With the club's growing size, and entry to [[the Football League]], they had to move to a new ground in 1903, [[Ayresome Park]].<ref name="PremierLeagueSite"/> It was designed by [[Archibald Leitch]] and would be the club's home for the next 92 years. Following the [[Taylor Report]] in 1990, the ground either needed modernising or the club needed a new stadium. The club decided on the latter, and moved out at the end of the 1994<U+2013>95 season. It was used as a training ground during 1995<U+2013>96, before it was demolished in 1997 and a housing estate built in its place.<ref name="GroundsHistory">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/grounds |title=Road to the Riverside |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.}}</ref> The club now trains at a <U+00A3>7&nbsp;million complex at [[Rockliffe Park (Hurworth)|Rockliffe Park]], in [[Hurworth-on-Tees|Hurworth]], on the outskirts of [[Darlington]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/rockliffe-park |title=Rockliffe Park |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.}}</ref>

The [[Riverside Stadium]], named by the supporters of the club after a vote, became the club's home in 1995. It was the first stadium to be built in line with the Taylor Report's recommendations on all-seater stadia for clubs in the top two divisions of the [[English football league system]].<ref name="Riverside Stadium">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/club/stadium-story|title=The Riverside Stadium |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.}}</ref> It was originally a 30,000 seater stadium, constructed at a cost of <U+00A3>16&nbsp;million,<ref name="RSStadium" /> before it was expanded in 1998 to a capacity of 35,100 for an extra <U+00A3>5&nbsp;million.<ref name="RSStadium"/>
The capacity of the stadium has since been reduced slightly to its current level of 34,988.

Average attendances at Middlesbrough matches have fluctuated over the past several years, moving from a 2004<U+2013>05 high average of 32,012 to a low of 26,092 in 2006<U+2013>07, then up again to 28,428 in 2008<U+2013>09. Following relegation to the Championship attendances have dipped, although the crowd of 23,451 which saw Middlesbrough's first Championship game against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] represents far higher gates than is usual for the division, and indeed larger than those of some [[Premier League]] clubs, for example [[Queens Park Rangers]] or [[Wigan Athletic]].

A reorganization of the Riverside Stadium occurred at the start of the 2013<U+2013>14 season. Away fans were moved from behind the goal at the South Stand to the East Stand whilst home fans can now sit behind the goal in an attempt to create a bigger atmosphere at the stadium. Also, a giant TV screen was placed in the South-East corner.<ref>{{cite news|first=Philip |last=Tallentire |url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/reorganisation-riverside-stadium-given-go-ahead-3665502 |title=Reorganisation of Riverside Stadium given go-ahead |work=Gazette Live |date=13 March 2013 |accessdate=8 December 2013}}</ref>

==Supporters==
Traditionally supporters come from Middlesbrough itself and towns in the immediate area. Middlesbrough have one of the highest proportions in Britain of locally born season ticket holders at 80%, and one of the highest proportions of female fans at 20%.<ref name="Football'sRich Pickings">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/1350453.stm |title=Football's Rich Pickings |accessdate=23 May 2007 |publisher=BBC  | date=25 May 2001}}</ref> A survey at the start of the 2007<U+2013>08 season found Middlesbrough supporters were the seventh loudest set of fans in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/26102007/58/premier-league-noise-league-table-sunderland-top.html |title=Premier League <U+2013> Noise League Table |publisher=Yahoo! Sport |date=26 October 2007 |accessdate=27 October 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071028091644/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/26102007/58/premier-league-noise-league-table-sunderland-top.html |archivedate = 28 October 2007}}</ref> [[File:Boro Eindhoven.jpg|Middlesbrough supporters at the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]]|left|thumb]] Middlesbrough Official Supporters Club, which features their own team in the local football league,<ref name="SupportersClub">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/fans/supporters-clubs |title=Supporters' Clubs |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.}}</ref> has links with supporters' clubs across the globe. The largest supporters' clubs include the Official Supporters' Club, the Middlesbrough Disabled Supporters' Association, Yarm Reds, Red Faction and Middlesbrough Supporters South.<ref name="SupportersClub" />

Middlesbrough supporters' main rivals are [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] (with whom they contest the [[Tees<U+2013>Wear derby]]), [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] (with whom they contest the [[Tyne<U+2013>Tees derby]]), and [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]], a fact confirmed by planetfootball.com's 2004 survey,<ref name="fan survey">{{cite web |url=http://www.footballfanscensus.com/issueresults/Club_Rivalries_Uncovered_Results.pdf |title=Club rivalries uncovered |publisher=footballfancensus |format=PDF |accessdate=13 October 2007}}</ref> where Sunderland and Newcastle fans also considered Middlesbrough to be amongst their top three rivalries. [[Carlisle United]] see Middlesbrough as their biggest rivals, but Middlesbrough supporters have not reciprocated, as they do not see Carlisle as a top three rival.

The nickname ''[[Smoggie]]s'' was first used as a derogatory term by opposing supporters;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2822465.stm |title=Football club bans gas masks |publisher=BBC News  |accessdate=26 May 2008 | date=5 March 2003}}</ref> it relates to the industrial air pollution (smog) that used to hang over the town, but it was later used by Middlesbrough fans in a somewhat self-deprecating manner before finally being adopted as a badge of pride by supporters of the club. An example of this can be seen on the banners carried to away games stating "Smoggies on Tour".<ref name="banners">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/fans/flags-and-banners/0,,1~618925,00.html |title=Banners |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> Middlesbrough fans were notably praised by [[UEFA]] Chief Executive [[Lars-Christer Olsson]] after their behaviour during the [[UEFA Cup 2005<U+2013>06|2005<U+2013>06 UEFA Cup campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/7164139._Impeccable__Boro_fans_win_praise/ |title='Impeccable' Boro fans win praise |date=20 May 2006 |accessdate=14 February 2014 |work=Northern Echo}}</ref> He commended that:{{quote|You have the satisfaction of knowing that, although your team did not win the game, your supporters present in Eindhoven proved to the world that football fans can turn a match into a friendly, violence-free celebration.}} Middlesbrough fans had also been praised by [[Cleveland Police]] for their behaviour in previous rounds, particularly in the light of aggravation prior to and during the match at [[A.S. Roma|Roma]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tees/4812092.stm |title=Boro fans praised for behaviour |date=16 March 2006 |accessdate=31 August 2007 |publisher=BBC News }}</ref>

==Media relations==
Middlesbrough were the first football club in the world to launch its own TV channel <U+2013> "Boro TV". The first broadcasts were tied to the club's first ever major cup final appearance in 1997, a full year ahead of Manchester United's MUTV, which still claims to be the first in the world. The channel was the brainchild of then NTL Markeking Director, Peter Wilcock. Its programmes were not 'live' initially but were pre-recorded and hosted by local radio/TV broadcaster & Boro fan, [[Dave Roberts (sports broadcaster)|Dave Roberts]]. Boro TV went on to claim another 'first' when in August 2001 it become the first English football club to broadcast time-delayed full-match footage of their league games on their own channel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportbusiness.com/news/100145/boro-first-to-take-advantage-of-new-tv-rights-regulations |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120817200017/http://www.sportbusiness.com/news/100145/boro-first-to-take-advantage-of-new-tv-rights-regulations |archivedate=17 August 2012 |title=Boro first to take advantage of new TV rights regulations |accessdate=31 August 2007 |date=31 August 2001 |publisher=sportbusiness.com}}</ref> Boro TV ran through [[Virgin Media|NTL]] cable television until July 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/middlesbrough/4641295.stm |title=Boro television channel to close |date=1 July 2005 |accessdate=31 August 2007 |publisher=BBC Sport }}</ref> The club now show match highlights through a subscription-based scheme on their official website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfc.co.uk |title=Official website |publisher=Middlesbrough FC|accessdate=31 August 2007}}</ref>

Middlesbrough's official matchday programme, ''Redsquare'', was ''Programme Monthly's'' 2006<U+2013>07 Programme of the Year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-fc-news/tm_headline=we-ll-be-spot-on&method=full&objectid=18751361&siteid=109975-name_page.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20101107032332/http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-fc-news/tm_headline=we-ll-be-spot-on&method=full&objectid=18751361&siteid=109975-name_page.html |archivedate=7 November 2010 |title=Success is taken as read (section title) |date=14 March 2007 |accessdate=10 October 2008 |work=Evening Gazette}}</ref> There are numerous other [[fanzine]]s available, most notably ''[[Fly Me to the Moon (fanzine)|Fly Me to the Moon]]'', formed in September 1988 following Bruce Rioch's quote to Tony Mowbray, stating "If I had to go to the moon I'd want him by my side".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-556192/Mowbray-miserable-sod-life-truly-kissed-angel.html |title=Mowbray, the 'miserable sod' whose life was truly kissed by an angel |work=Daily Mail |location=UK |date=13 April 2008 |accessdate=3 April 2008 |first=Alan |last=Fraser}}</ref>

==Community==
'''Middlesbrough Football Club in the Community''' (MFCIC) was founded in 1995 by club chairman [[Steve Gibson (businessman)|Steve Gibson]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~3107912,00.html |title=MFC Foundation Launched |accessdate=14 February 2014 |publisher=mfc.co.uk}}</ref> and is the largest community-based football scheme in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~1168641,00.html |title=Blair Praises Community Role |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> It is run separately from the football club but receives support from both the club in terms of providing players, staff, stadium facilities and [[Public relations|PR]] in the matchday programme and other publications, as well as support from other local organisations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfcic.co.uk/mfcic/corporate/funders_and_sponsors.html |title=Funders and Sponsors |accessdate=10 December 2007 |publisher=mfcic.co.uk |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070519202346/http://www.mfcic.co.uk/mfcic/corporate/funders_and_sponsors.html |archivedate = 19 May 2007}}</ref>

Since 2002, the club and MFCIC have also run the Middlesbrough Enterprise Academy, a scheme which helps local children improve their entrepreneurial skills and increase their awareness of business planning and finance. In March 2008, plans were announced by the Premier League to roll out the scheme nationally amongst all Premier League clubs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~1264934,00.html |title=Boro Inspire Enterprise Push |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |date=14 March 2008 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>

It was announced in December 2007 that Middlesbrough football club had carried out more community work during [[2006<U+2013>07 in English football|2006<U+2013>07]] than any other [[Premier League]] club, rising from second place the previous year, with the club making 318 appearances <U+2013> almost twice the Premier League average of 162.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/boro-are-charity-champs-3737289 |title=Boro are charity champs |work=Evening Gazette |date=10 December 2007 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref> They were in the top two for community appearances again in 2007<U+2013>08, with 374 <U+2013> a 17% increase on the previous season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/ClubNewsDetail/0,,1~1499019,00.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090418013932/http://www.mfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/ClubNewsDetail/0,,1~1499019,00.html |archivedate=18 April 2009 |title=Boro Heroes Star in the Community |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |date=24 December 2008 |accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref>

Middlesbrough's mascot is Roary the Lion. The club runs Roary's Children's Charity Fund which purchases items for local children's charities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/ClubNewsDetail/0,,1~586586,00.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20090303052041/http://www.mfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/ClubNewsDetail/0,,1~586586,00.html|archivedate=3 March 2009|title=Boro's Annual Charter Report|accessdate=26 January 2008 |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C.}}</ref>

In 2009, steel producer [[Corus Group]] announced the possibility that it would mothball its Teesside plant, with up to 4,000 employees and contractors facing redundancy, after a consortium of steel magnates walked away from a 10-year deal. Middlesbrough Football Club helped with the "Save Our Steel" campaign by hosting dozens of steel workers and their families as they marched around the ground, promoted the campaign via the stadium's PA system, scoreboards and in match day programmes, while players wore t-shirts during warm-ups promoting the campaign.<ref name="SaveOurSteel1"/> Chairman [[Steve Gibson (businessman)|Steve Gibson]] said:

{{quote|"Middlesbrough Football Club exists for the community, for the people of Teesside<U+2014>and the closure of the steel plants threatens to rip the heart out of our community. We cannot stand by and allow that to happen. We want the steelworkers and their families to know that we are behind them and will help their campaign in any way we can ... We like to think that the football club is the flagship of Teesside. Well this is our town and these are our people and we have to do what we can to help them."<ref name="SaveOurSteel1">{{cite news|url=http://www.mfc.co.uk/page/news/latest/0,,1~1798024,00.html |title=Boro's Steel Fight Goes On |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |date=16 September 2009 |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>}}

